# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1794–95 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 25, 1794 (New Hampshire), and September 5, 1795 (Kentucky).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 4th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1795.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held during President George Washington's second term.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 105 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the first election for the House of Representatives with organized political parties, the Democratic-Republican Party, which opposed the incumbent Washington Administration, defeated the pro-administration Federalist Party.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The outgoing speaker, Frederick Muhlenberg, had supported the pro-administration forces during his first two terms, but was elected by a coalition made up mainly of anti-administration members in 1793, and by 1795 he was seen as more favorable to the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite the Democratic-Republican majority, however, Muhlenberg was not re-elected, and was succeeded by Federalist Jonathan Dayton.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 3rd and 4th Congresses in 1794 and 1795.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only two candidates are recorded for Delaware's congressional election in 1794, suggesting that the voting procedure in place for the first three Congresses for two candidates had been changed.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts redistricted between the 3rd and 4th Congress, dividing itself into 14 districts.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 12th-14th districts were in the District of Maine (the modern State of Maine).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Additional ballots were required in five districts due to the majority requirement not being met on the first ballot.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under New Hampshire's electoral laws, a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required for election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only three candidates achieved a majority, and so a run-off election was held for the fourth seat.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, but were later numbered retroactively.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania once again divided itself into districts instead of electing representatives at-large, as it had for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The state divided intself into 12 districts, one of which (the 4th) had two seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania would continue to use one or more plural districts until 1842.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Electoral data are only available for the 1st and 5th district of South Carolina's 6 districts at the time of the elections of 1794.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representative-elect Barnwell of the 2nd district declined to serve.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A special election was held to fill the resulting vacancy, electing Wade Hampton (Democratic-Republican).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a majority for election to Congress, with a second election to be held if the first did not return a majority.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Run-off elections were required in both districts.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1796–97 United States House of Representatives elections** took place in the various states between August 12, 1796 (in North Carolina), and October 15, 1797 (in Tennessee).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 106 seats after Tennessee became the 16th U.S. state to join the union.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the 5th United States Congress was convened on May 15, 1797, at the proclamation of the new President of the United States, John Adams.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since Kentucky and Tennessee had not yet voted, they were unrepresented until the second session began on November 13, 1797.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Gains for the Federalist Party provided the president with a reliable majority in support of his policies.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many of the Federalist pick-ups in Congress came from the former Middle Colonies (New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and Delaware).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New England remained heavily Federalist, whereas the South and West favored Democratic-Republican candidates.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federalist trade and infrastructure policies found widespread approval in the Mid-Atlantic states during this era.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the growth of cities in Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New York, government intervention in the interest of industrialization and mercantilism became more attractive to voting citizens in these areas.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 1st session of the 5th Congress ran May 15 – July 10, 1797, before the states of Kentucky and Tennessee had their elections, causing those states to be unrepresented in the 1st session.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by election date, then by district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 4th Congress in 1796.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 5th Congress in 1797.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected its seven representatives at-large on a general ticket.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two of the four Democratic-Republicans were replaced by Federalists, bringing the Federalists from a 4–4 split to a 6–2 majority.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election, necessitating additional trials in three districts.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1796, New Hampshire had a single at-large district with 4 seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each voter cast 4 votes and a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required to be elected.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since only three candidates received a majority, a run-off was held between the candidates in fourth and fifth place to fill the remaining seat.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island had an at-large district with two seats, each of which were elected separately.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to Vermont's law requiring a majority to secure a congressional seat, the 1st district required three ballots to choose a winner.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1798–99 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 24, 1798, in New York and August 1, 1799, in Tennessee.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives, with some after the official start of the 6th United States Congress on March 4, 1799, but before the start of the first session of this Congress in Philadelphia on December 2, 1799.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These elections were held during President John Adams' term.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It was the last congressional session before the move to the new capital at Washington, D.C.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 106 seats, representing 16 states.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This resulted in an increased Federalist majority in the House, 60-46 seats.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalist party squandered its popularity by passing a series of controversial new laws in the summer of 1798, including the Naturalization Act of 1798 and the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their passage seriously injured the chances of President Adams and Federalist congressional candidates in the elections of 1800.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The House that met during this Congress would ultimately elect Thomas Jefferson over Aaron Burr in the presidential election of 1800.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1798 and 1799 during the 5th United States Congress and 6th United States Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by date then district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority for election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was not met in the 5th district and 7th district necessitating additional ballots in those districts.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Jersey switched to district representation for this election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The districts were not numbered at the time, but are retroactively numbered here as 1–5.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Jersey would go back to an at-large district the following election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Between the 1796 and 1798 elections, New York re-districted.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This marked the first time that its districts were numbered.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island used at-large districts, but elected the candidates on separate tickets instead of using a general ticket.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Majority vote required to win, necessitating a run-off election in the 1st (Western) district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1800–01 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 29, 1800, and August 1, 1801.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 7th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1801.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held at the same time as the 1800 presidential election, in which Vice President Thomas Jefferson, a Democratic Republican, defeated incumbent President John Adams, a Federalist.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 106 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These elections resulted in the Democratic-Republicans picking up 22 seats from the Federalists.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This brought the Democratic-Republicans a solid majority of 68 seats, whereas the Federalists were only able to secure 38.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many state legislatures also changed to Democratic-Republican control, with the result that many new Democratic-Republicans were voted into the Senate.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists never again succeeded in gaining a majority of seats in the House of Representatives, and the national Federalist Party disintegrated completely in the early 1820s.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The victory of Jefferson and the Democratic-Republicans can be attributed partially to unpopular policies pursued by the Adams administration, including the Alien and Sedition Acts, which sought to curtail guarantees of freedom of speech and freedom of the press spelled out in the Bill of Rights.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The difference between Federalist policies in support of a strong national government and the Democratic-Republican preference for states' rights played a prominent role in the election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federal taxation became an issue as Southerners and Westerners rejected federal taxes levied on property.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1800 and 1801 during the 6th United States Congress and 7th United States Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Note: Between the two sources used, there is disagreement over the ordering of the candidates.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are ordered here as Goddard and Talmadge in 8th and 9th place as it is more likely that they'd been at the top of the runners-up given that they were subsequently elected to fill vacancies in the 7th Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election, which was not met in the 1st and 6th districts, necessitating a second trial.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1800, New Jersey returned to its traditional at-large district, continued to use this system to select representatives until it was abolished in 1842, with a single exception in 1813.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island switched to a general ticket for its two seats, instead of electing each one separately.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only one candidate received a majority in the 1800 election, requiring an 1801 run-off election to choose a Representative for the second seat.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a candidate to win a majority to take office, necessitating a run-off election in the 2nd (Eastern) district.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] From December 3, 1855, to February 2, 1856, the incoming House of Representatives held an election for speaker of the U.S.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] After one hundred and thirty-two inconclusive ballots, Nathaniel Prentiss Banks of Massachusetts was elected over William Aiken Jr. of South Carolina pursuant to a temporary rule permitting a candidate to be elected with a plurality of the vote.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The election was dominated by debate over slavery and the Kansas-Nebraska Act, and contemporary reaction recognized Banks's victory as the first "Northern victory" in the events leading to the American Civil War.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Following the 1854–55 United States House of Representatives elections, opponents of the incumbent Franklin Pierce administration won a large majority of the seats in the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] However, the anti-administration representatives-elect, grouped together informally as the "Opposition," had little common ground and no common party organization.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Five Opposition candidates were formally nominated, but the race soon coalesced around two Opposition figures, Nathaniel P.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks of Massachusetts and Henry Mills Fuller of Pennsylvania, against Democratic nominee William Alexander Richardson.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks gained the formal nomination of the Opposition but repeatedly fell short of a majority of the House as many members of the Opposition, primarily Southern nativists or anti-abolitionists, cast their votes for Fuller or other Opposition candidates.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On the final day of balloting, members of Democratic minority agreed to the use of plurality voting, having settled on South Carolina unionist William Aiken Jr. as a compromise candidate who could win the votes of the southern Opposition.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On the final ballot, Aiken gained most of the dissident Opposition votes but fell three short of Banks.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] As of 2026, this remains the longest election for speaker in the history of the United States House, both in terms of ballots and duration, and a record 135 people received votes.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks remains one of only two Speakers, with Howell Cobb in 1849, elected by plurality.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] In May 1854, the 33rd Congress passed the Kansas–Nebraska Act with support from President Franklin Pierce, Senator Stephen Douglas of Illinois, and pro-slavery Democratic members of the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The Act repealed the 1820 Missouri Compromise and the Compromise of 1850 by establishing a path to statehood for the territories of Kansas and Nebraska and allowing these new states to permit or prohibit slavery by popular referendum.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The Kansas-Nebraska Act was regarded as a major victory for pro-slavery activists, as the two Compromises had previously restricted any further legalization of slavery to lands south of parallel 36°30′ north.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The new possibility of slavery north of this parallel inflamed political tensions, especially in the Northern United States, and immediately triggered a trend of political migration to the territories in hopes of influencing the first territorial elections.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The political reaction was immediately negative for Pierce and the Democratic Party.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Elections to the House of Representatives were held in thirty-one states for all 234 seats between August 4, 1854, and November 6, 1855.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Each state legislature separately set a date to elect members to the House of Representatives before the 34th Congress convened its first session on December 3, 1855.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] These elections were among the most disruptive in American history, bringing the total collapse of the Second Party System.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Candidates opposed to the Kansas–Nebraska Act and the administration, included disaffected Democratic voters, won widely in the North from April 1854 through November 1855, but the Whig Party did not reap the benefit.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] By 1854, most leading national Whigs, e.g., Henry Clay and Daniel Webster, had died, and the party had limited success in recent national elections.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The Whigs were associated with big business and seen as elitist and unresponsive to the concerns of the American people over slavery, immigration, industrialization, and monopoly power.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Many new anti-administration representatives were elected on a fusion ticket with support from multiple parties, and many were political novices who frankly admitted they had not expected to be elected.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Taken together, the opposition parties, including the Whigs and the old anti-slavery Free Soil Party, won an estimated net gain of 69 seats nationwide and made up a sizable majority of the House in the 34th Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] However, due to the confused and overlapping nature of the anti-Nebraska opposition, contemporaries and historians have had difficulty defining the precise makeup of the 34th Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The *Congressional Globe* failed to list party labels in its opening session guide, and according to historian George H.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Representatives-elect also varied in the importance they placed on slavery as an issue.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Many of the American Party representatives-elect, though opposed to the Kansas-Nebraska Act, prioritized the issue of immigration and were willing to compromise with pro-Nebraska Democrats in order to gain support for immigration restriction or anti-Catholic measures.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] As the 34th Congress prepared to meet in its first session, scheduled for December 1855, tensions between Kansas settlers came to a head in the outbreak of political violence.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] In a conflict which would later come to be known as "Bleeding Kansas," the status of slavery was violently disputed between anti-slavery Free-Staters and pro-slavery Border Ruffians from neighboring Missouri.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The settlement of Kansas and especially the activism of emigrant aid companies like the New England Emigrant Aid Company heightened national attention on slavery and Kansas.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] In June 1855, the national American Party council split over the issue of slavery into its northern and southern wings.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] As autumn approached, anti-slavery activists and journalists began to congregate in Washington in hopes of organizing the House under an anti-slavery majority.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] These efforts were boosted on the eve of the opening session, when the administration Democrats adopted a caucus resolution authored by J.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Glancy Jones of Pennsylvania which severely denounced nativism and the Know Nothing movement, thus leaving the southern American representatives-elect without any potential coalition partner.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Despite these apparent advantages, organizing anti-slavery men behind a single candidate before the vote failed.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Day privately remarked, "There are about thirty *modest* men who think the country needs their services in the Speaker's chair.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The speaker is the presiding officer of the U.S.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The House elects its speaker at the beginning of each new Congress (i.e., biennially) or when a speaker dies, resigns, or is removed from the position intra-term.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Since 1839, the House has elected speakers by roll call vote.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Following an election, there being no speaker, the outgoing clerk summons, convenes, and calls the House to order.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] They then order and oversee the election of a speaker of the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Upon winning election, the new speaker is immediately sworn in by the dean of the U.S.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] House of Representatives, the chamber's longest-serving member.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The new speaker then administers the oath en masse to the rest of the members of the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] To be elected speaker, a candidate typically must receive an absolute majority of the votes cast, as opposed to an absolute majority of the full membership of the House.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] A variation in the number of votes necessary to win a given election might arise due to vacancies, absentees, or members being present but not voting.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Multiple roll calls had been necessary eleven times since 1789.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] This had happened most recently in 1849, when Howell Cobb was elected by a plurality on the 63rd ballot, a record at the time.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The election for speaker began on December 3, 1855, at the start of the 34th Congress.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] At the opening of the session, George W.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Jones of Tennessee moved to proceed viva voce to an election of a speaker.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Before balloting began, candidates were placed into nomination, though a candidate need not be nominated to receive votes or win the election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Richardson stood as the formally nominated candidate of the Democratic caucus as leader of the minority.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks, Campbell, Fuller, and Pennington stood as anti-Nebraska candidates opposed to the extension of slavery, while Marshall stood as a southern, pro-Nebraska American Party candidate.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The anti-Nebraska faction split regionally, with Banks leading New England, Campbell leading Ohio and the Great Lakes, and Fuller and Pennington supported by their home states of Pennsylvania and New Jersey, respectively.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] From the first ballot, it became clear that the anti-Nebraska majority were completely divided.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Seventeen anti-Nebraska candidates polled votes, with none receiving over a quarter of the total.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Richardson led the first ballot with 74 votes, with Campbell leading the opposition at 55.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Marshall received 39 votes, Banks received 22, Fuller received 18, and Pennington received 7.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Two more ballots were taken with similar results.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] To further confuse matters, four anti-Nebraska Democrats voted with their party for Richardson and three anti-slavery Know Nothings voted for Marshall.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The first two days of the election were dominated by the search for an anti-slavery candidate.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Campbell consistently led the coalition on early ballots but fell well short of a majority, as a significant number of votes went to Nathaniel Banks.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks, a former Democratic–Free Soil politician, presented as a natural alternative to Campbell, a former Whig.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] At a general anti-Nebraska conference, the coalition agreed to push Campbell's vote as high as possible and, if it proved he could not be elected, throw their support behind Banks.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] If Banks also failed, Pennington would have been the candidate.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Thus, on December 5, the third day of balloting, Campbell reached eighty-one votes but remained thirty short of a majority, as anti-slavery conservatives and anti-Nebraska Democrats refused their support.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On December 6, before the start of balloting, Thomas R.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Whitney withdrew the name of Humphrey Marshall, the southern American Party candidate, from the running.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The same day, Campbell's support collapsed as anti-slavery votes scattered to Banks, Pennington, and other candidates.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On December 7, between the twenty-third and twenty-fourth ballots, Campbell withdrew his name from contention.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Campbell's bitter withdrawal cast a shadow over the anti-slavery coalition for the remainder of the contest.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] He was quoted in the *New York Herald* referring to Banks as a "dead cock in the pit" and frequently voted against him on subsequent ballots.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] His accompanying statement also became a major issue on ensuing ballots, as the minority accused the fledgling Republican Party of attempting to secure the speakership by an improper quid pro quo.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] With Campbell now out of the race, his supporters split further between Banks, Pennington, and others including Felix Zollicoffer of Tennessee and Benjamin B.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On the twenty-fourth ballot, the first after Campbell's withdrawal, Banks received only forty votes but led the opposition.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] He gained steadily and, after a night of conferences, emerged on December 8 with one hundred votes.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] By December 10, he had gained two more, coming within a half dozen of a majority and the speakership.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] He would remain at that margin for the rest of the contest.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] As Banks began to stall over the next few days, Pennington supporters claimed their candidate should be given a turn, but on December 14, an anti-Nebraska caucus officially named Banks their nominee.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] With Banks as the nominee, the anti-slavery faction focused on rallying persuadable votes and keeping their ranks closed.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Some thought him too extreme or too mild on slavery.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Others questioned his convictions on other issues, such as nativism or protectionism, or opposed him because of the support he received from the New York Tribune, personal rivalries, or ambition.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks's campaign was headed in the House by Anson Burlingame, Schuyler Colfax, and the three Washburn brothers, Cadwallader, Elihu, and Israel Jr.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] They planned a three-pronged strategy in Washington to pressure swing votes, which included a letter-writing and telegraph campaign from constituents, personal appeals to representatives-elect from like-minded Banks supporters, and direct lobbying by agents on Banks's behalf.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The lobbying efforts were the most controversial prong of the campaign, as opponents accused the Banks men of bribery during and after the election.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Journalists and politicians branded the anti-Nebraska men who opposed Banks as "doughfaces" and organized anti-slavery conferences to support Banks.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Meanwhile, Fuller abandoned the anti-Nebraska cause entirely.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Beginning with Marshall's withdrawal, Fuller began negotiations with Marshall and Richardson supporters in hopes of forming a coalition of pro-Nebraska Americans, administration Democrats, and Fuller's personal friends.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] By the eighth, most of Marshall's support had shifted to Fuller, who in turn shed his own initial support in Pennsylvania.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] As early as December 10, when Banks peaked at 107 votes, efforts were made to secure his victory without a majority.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Representative Jacob Broom of Pennsylvania sought to curtail debate by proposing a petition to the Supreme Court to request an advisory opinion on the constitutionality of Congressional regulation of slavery in the territories, previewing the upcoming arguments in the *Dred Scott v.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] By Christmas, administration Democrats began to discuss support for a continuous session or plurality rule.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] President Pierce urged the resumption of business, and there was genuine belief in the possibility of a Democratic victory if the Fuller men were forced to choose between Richardson and Banks.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] However, these efforts died out after Pierce delivered his message without issue.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On January 9, the House began an all-night session proposed by Democratic leaders, primarily to prevent an election by plurality.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Through eighteen hours of debate and balloting, no candidate lost or gained significant footing.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] At eight o'clock a.m. the next day, with attendance dwindling, the pro-Nebraska men joined to adjourn the chamber.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Soon after, Fuller supporters seeking to embarrass Richardson and force a fusion behind their candidate called for a "catechism" designed to investigate the political views of the three leading candidates on slavery in the territories, the Fugitive Slave Act, nativism, and white supremacy.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Each candidate was affected by their responses to the survey.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Fuller's gambit paid off, strengthening his hold on the pro-Nebraska Know Nothings while weakening support for his opponents.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Richardson's failure to denounce the Wilmot Proviso as an unconstitutional restriction on slavery offended some Democratic loyalists, and three South Carolinians deserted him on the next ballot.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks was assailed as an "amalgamationist" for his views on race, harming his chances at victory, and he eventually publicly recanted his remarks.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Under pressure from President Pierce, administration men sought a compromise.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] After offers to vote by plurality in exchange for Banks's withdrawal failed, Albert Rust of Arkansas introduced a resolution to force the leading candidates to withdraw.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The resolution, aimed at Banks, implied that personal ambitions stood in the way of organization.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] However, Banks men allied with a half dozen administration Democrats to defeat the motion.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] With Richardson voting in favor, he was forced to withdraw to save his reputation.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Before the start of balloting, Richardson announced that, "after today my name will be unconditionally withdrawn from the pending canvass for the speakership. ...
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] I hope this course may lead to a speedy organization.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] I fear that discord will still reign in this Hall, and that history will record the fact as an evidence against our ability for self-government." He was succeeded by James L.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Orr of South Carolina as the Democratic caucus nominee.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] From the time Richardson withdrew onwards, debate focused on the plurality rule, with some administration men who sought to finally organize the House joining Banks men in support.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Clingman of North Carolina moved for elections by plurality, along the lines of the 1849 resolution.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Clingman's resolution divided the Democratic Party and the South.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] He argued that a failure to vote against Banks or Orr in a direct decision in fact meant that the voter "prefers him, of course, to the other." Several Democratic representatives spoke out against the motion.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Herbert of California spoke in favor while denouncing those willing to "clothe [Banks] with power, who but a few days since expressed in their own hearing a doubt as to the superiority of the white man over the negro." William W.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Boyce of South Carolina denounced "a single step toward the election of Mr.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Banks... as one of the greatest misfortunes that could happen to this country ... as death to the Constitution and the Union." The resolution was voted down 106 to 110.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The next day, it was reintroduced and failed 108 to 110.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Sensing that Clingman's resolution and the narrow vote of January 31 meant the plurality rule would soon be adopted, Alexander H.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Stephens of Georgia privately proposed to allow the plurality rule to go into effect and substitute William Aiken Jr. of South Carolina before the final ballot.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Unlike Orr, Aiken was not an active member of the caucus and had expressed no opinion on nativism, having avoided the caucus in which J.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The Stephens plan gained the quiet support of the southern Know Nothing representatives-elect who had thus far voted for Fuller.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On February 1, representatives-elect offered several names, including Banks and Stephens, to be elected Speaker directly by resolution.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Despite Stephens's plan to spring Aiken's name as a surprise only after a plurality rule was adopted, representatives-elect Williamson Cobb of Alabama and John Kelly of New York offered Aiken as a nominee directly.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The Aiken resolution survived a motion to table by a vote of 98 to 117, and though Aiken was defeated by 103 to 110, he received several opposition votes.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Though Cobb and Kelly had also cost Stephens the element of surprise, Aiken's total vote and ability to rally pro-Nebraska men and Fuller men raised Democratic confidence.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Last-ditch efforts to pass a compromise resolution, including one to appoint Banks, Aiken, and Fuller to vote on a Speaker as a committee of three, failed.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On February 2, the House floor and galleries were packed as most anticipated the adoption of the plurality rule and the election of a Speaker.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The day opened with a motion to proceed under plurality rule was reintroduced by Samuel A.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Smith of Tennessee, a pro-Nebraska administration man.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] The balloting proceeded despite repeated efforts to adjourn, with Banks, Aiken, and Fuller all receiving votes.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On the fourth and final ballot of the day, Banks narrowly defeated Aiken 103 to 100.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Six northern representatives-elect (Jacob Broom, Bayard Clark, Elisha D.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Cullen, Henry Winter Davis, William Millward, and Thomas R.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Four others from Indiana and Ohio (George G.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Campbell, and John Hickman voted for Daniel Wells Jr. of Wisconsin.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Though some in the minority claimed that Banks had not been elected until a formal resolution declared him Speaker, debate ended when Aiken asked permission to escort Banks to the chair himself.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Joshua Giddings, as dean of the House, swore Banks in as Speaker after his election on February 2.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Contemporaries immediately began to refer to Banks's election as the "first Northern victory" in the emerging sectional conflict over slavery which would lead to the American Civil War.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Opinion was largely divided along sectional lines.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] In the North and among abolitionists, the election was acclaimed as a long-awaited victory over the Slave Power.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Hundred-gun saltues were fired in several New England cities.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Some Democratic unionists took a subdued response.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] William Lloyd Garrison wrote in his *Liberator*, "Let us hope that this result is but the first gun at Lexington of the new Revolution.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] If so, then Bunker Hill and Yorktown are before us!
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Historians have noted Banks as the initial symbol of the emerging Republican Party and his speakership as the origin point of the party's institutional organization.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Immediately after the election, Giddings remarked, "We have got our party formed, consolidated and established." Thurlow Weed commented, "This triumph is worth all it cost in time, toil and solicitude ... [for] the Republican Party is now inaugurated.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] A spatial analysis of the speakership election conducted by Jeffrey A.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] Nokken concluded that the voting patterns of individual members during the election were predictable from the outset as a function of their respective positions on slavery, whereas nativism had greater variability with any individual member's vote.
[src:1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election/1855-56-speaker-of-the-united-states-house-of-representatives-election] On the final ballot, the split of the Fuller supporters between Banks and Aiken was highly predictable by both region and position on slavery.
